        { text: "Choose a simple melody — the verse of a song you know, or just Am pentatonic: A-C-D-E-D-C-A. You'll sing this same melody four times, each in a different genre voice." },
        { text: "Reggae voice (2 min): behind-the-beat timing, relaxed jaw, warm chest resonance, minimal vibrato. Phrases that float behind the guitar strum. Think Protoje, Chronixx. The voice LAGS the beat by a hair.", why: "Reggae vocal production is defined by rhythmic relationship to the beat, not by tone. The warmth comes from chest resonance at moderate volume. No pushing, no projection — the mic does the work. Behind-the-beat timing is the defining characteristic." },
        { text: "Surf-psych voice (2 min): forward placement, bright vowels, moderate reverb quality (sing as if the room has echo), slight drawl. Think Allah-Las, BALTHVS. The voice is present but unhurried.", why: "Surf-psych vocals sit in a specific resonance zone — forward enough to be bright, relaxed enough to be cool. The 'reverb quality' is about vowel openness and sustain, not about effects. When you hear Allah-Las vocals dry, they STILL sound reverb-drenched because of how the vowels are shaped." },
        { text: "Desert blues voice (2 min): lower register (stay below passaggio), dark vowels, sustained tones, minimal ornament. Think Tinariwen, Bombino. The voice is a drone — hypnotic, repetitive, channeling rather than performing.", why: "Desert blues vocals are the most physically distinctive — low register, minimal range movement, dark 'ah' and 'oh' vowels. The style demands that the singer BECOME the drone, not sing over it. Body should be still and grounded. This is the opposite of the movement encouragement in other exercises — desert blues demands physical rootedness." },
        { text: "Lo-fi/intimate voice (2 min): breathy tone (incomplete vocal fold closure), very close to the mic (or imagine being very close), almost whispered dynamics, DOPE LEMON territory. The voice is private — singing for yourself, not an audience.", why: "Breathy tone is achieved by allowing a controlled air leak through the vocal folds — the folds don't fully adduct, letting some unphonated air through. This is a deliberate technique in lo-fi and bedroom pop, not a vocal flaw. Angus Stone has built an entire career on this breathy, intimate vocal production." },
        { text: "Listen to all four recordings back to back. Which genre voice felt most natural? Which required the most effort? Which surprised you? The most natural one is your current vocal identity. The others are tools you're building. Write down: 'My natural voice is [genre]. I want to develop [genre].' This shapes your practice focus going forward." }
